{"title_page": "Guy Mainwaring Morton", "text_new": "{{Underlinked|date=April 2020}}\n\n'''Guy Mainwaring Morton''' (1896\u20131968) was a barrister and author who wrote under his own name and the pen name of '''Peter Traill'''.<ref>http://oxfordindex.oup.com/view/10.1093/ww/9780199540884.013.U57795</ref>\n\nHe married Clare, the daughter of the Hartlepool ship-owner [[M. H. Horsley|M.H. Horsley]], in 1923.<ref>\"Marriages\", ''The Times'', 29 October 1923, p. 15.</ref>\n\n==Selected publications==\n* ''Great Dust''. Grayson & Grayson, 1932.\n* ''The 3-7-9 Murder''\n* ''The Red Lady''\n* ''The Ragged Robin Murders''\n* ''The Perrin Murder Case''\n* ''Ashes of Murder''\n* ''Mystery at Hardacres''\n* ''The Forbidden Road''\n* ''The Angel''\n* ''The Scarlet Thumb-Print''\n* ''The Black Robe''\n* ''Under The Cherry Tree''\n* ''Rangy Pete''\n* ''King of the World, or, The Pommeray Case''\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Morton, Guy}}\n[[Category:1896 births]]\n[[Category:1968 deaths]]\n[[Category:English barristers]]\n[[Category:English writers]]\n\n\n{{UK-writer-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Guy Mainwaring Morton''' (1896\u20131968) was a barrister and author who wrote under his own name and the pen name of '''Peter Traill'''.<ref>http://oxfordindex.oup.com/view/10.1093/ww/9780199540884.013.U57795</ref>\n\nHe married Clare, the daughter of the Hartlepool ship-owner [[M. H. Horsley|M.H. Horsley]], in 1923.<ref>\"Marriages\", ''The Times'', 29 October 1923, p. 15.</ref>\n\n==Selected publications==\n* ''Great Dust''. Grayson & Grayson, 1932.\n* ''The 3-7-9 Murder''\n* ''The Red Lady''\n* ''The Ragged Robin Murders''\n* ''The Perrin Murder Case''\n* ''Ashes of Murder''\n* ''Mystery at Hardacres''\n* ''The Forbidden Road''\n* ''The Angel''\n* ''The Scarlet Thumb-Print''\n* ''The Black Robe''\n* ''Under The Cherry Tree''\n* ''Rangy Pete''\n* ''King of the World, or, The Pommeray Case''\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSO