{"title_page": "Guy Dynevor Thornton", "text_new": "{{Orphan|date=November 2012}}\n\n'''Guy Dynevor Thornton''' (1872&ndash;1934) was a notable New Zealand evangelist, army chaplain, and writer. He was born in [[Wotton-under-Edge]], [[Gloucestershire]], [[England]] in 1872.<ref name=\"DNZB Thornton\">{{DNZB|title=Guy Dynevor Thornton|first= Angus|last= MacLeod|id=3t35|accessdate=23 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Thornton, Guy Dynevor}}\n[[Category:1872 births]]\n[[Category:1934 deaths]]\n[[Category:New Zealand military personnel]]\n[[Category:New Zealand religious leaders]]\n[[Category:English emigrants to New Zealand]]\n[[Category:New Zealand writers]]\n\n\n{{NewZealand-mil-bio-stub}}\n{{NewZealand-writer-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Orphan|date=November 2012}}\n\n'''Guy Dynevor Thornton''' (1872&ndash;1934) was a notable New Zealand evangelist, army chaplain, and writer. He was born in [[Wotton-under-Edge]], [[Gloucestershire]], [[England]] in 1872.<ref name=\"DNZB Thornton\">{{DNZB|title=Guy Dynevor Thornton|first= Angus|last= MacLeod|id=3t35|accessdate=23 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Thornton, Guy Dynevor}}\n[[Category:1872 births]]\n[[Category:1934 deaths]]\n[[Category:New Zealand military personnel]]\n[[Category:New Zealand religious leaders]]\n[[Category:English emigrants to New Zealand]]\n[[Category:New Zealand writers]]\n\n\n{{NewZealand-mil-bio-stub}}\n{{NewZealand-writer-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Guy_Dynevor_Thornton"}
{"title_page": "Alliance of Small Island States", "text_new": "{{refimprove|date=January 2013}}\n\n'''Alliance of Small Island States''' ('''AOSIS''') is an [[intergovernmental organization]] of [[wikt:low lying|low-lying]] [[coast]]al and small [[island country|island countries]]. Established in 1990, the main purpose of the alliance is to consolidate the voices of [[Small Island Developing States]] (SIDS) to address [[global warming]]. AOSIS has been very active from its inception, putting forward the first draft text in the [[Kyoto Protocol]] negotiations as early as 1994. At the [[2013 United Nations Climate Change Conference|2013 Warsaw climate change conference]], AOSIS also pushed for the establishment of an international mechanism on loss and damages stressed by the wreckage of [[Supertyphoon Haiyan]].<ref>{{cite web|title=For Immediate Release: Small Islands Call For Urgency in Warsaw in Wake of Deadly Typhoon|date=11 November 2013|website=AOSIS|url=http://aosis.org/for-immediate-release-small-islands-call-for-urgency-in-warsaw-in-wake-of-deadly-typhoon/|access-date=12 December 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141026120745/http://aosis.org/for-immediate-release-small-islands-call-for-urgency-in-warsaw-in-wake-of-deadly-typhoon/|archive-date=26 October 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> As the existence of many AOSIS states are put at risk by climate change AOSIS has threatened lawsuits. The results of a recent review of the literature <ref>{{cite journal | author = Heidari Negin, Pearce Joshua M | year = 2016 | title = A Review of Greenhouse Gas Emission Liabilities as the Value of Renewable Energy for Mitigating Lawsuits for Climate Change Related Damages | url = https://www.academia.edu/19418589/A_Review_of_Greenhouse_Gas_Emission_Liabilities_as_the_Value_of_Renewable_Energy_for_Mitigating_Lawsuits_for_Climate_Change_Related_Damages |journal=[[Renewable and Sustainable Energy Reviews]] |volume = 55 | issue = | pages = 899\u2013908 | doi = 10.1016/j.rser.2015.11.025 }}</ref> show that potential liability for [[climate change]]-related losses for the Alliance of Small Island States is over $570 trillion.\n\nMany of the member states were present at the December [[2009 United Nations Climate Change Conference]] ([[COP15]]). [[Democracy Now!]] reported that members from the [[island state]] of [[Tuvalu]] interrupted a session of the [[2009 United Nations Climate Change Conference]] on 10 December 2009 to demand that global temperature rise be limited to 1.5 [[\u00b0C]] instead of the proposed 2&nbsp;\u00b0C.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.democracynow.org/2009/12/10/citing_its_survival_pacific_island_of|title=Citing Its Survival, Pacific Island of Tuvalu Interrupts Copenhagen Summit to Call for Binding Climate Commitments|website=Democracy Now!}}</ref><ref>\n{{Cite journal\n | year=2011\n | author=[[United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change]] (UNFCCC)\n | title=Conference of the Parties&nbsp;\u2013 Sixteenth Session: Decision 1/CP.16: The Cancun Agreements: Outcome of the work of the Ad Hoc Working Group on Long-term Cooperative Action under the Convention (English): Paragraph 4\n | publisher=UNFCCC\n | location=UNFCCC Secretariat: [[Bonn]], Germany\n | page=3\n | url=http://unfccc.int/resource/docs/2010/cop16/eng/07a01.pdf#page=2\n | format=PDF\n | ref=harv\n\n}} \"(...) deep cuts in global greenhouse gas emissions are required according to science, and as documented in the Fourth Assessment Report of the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change, with a view to reducing global greenhouse gas emissions so as to hold the increase in global average temperature below {{val|2|u=\u00b0C}} above preindustrial levels\"</ref>\n\nAOSIS has a membership of 44 states, of which 37 are members of the [[United Nations]], 2 ([[Cook Islands]] and [[Niue]]) participate within the United Nations, and five are [[Observer status|observers]] from all around the world. The alliance represents 28% of the [[developing countries]], and 20% of the [[Member states of the United Nations|UN's total membership]].\n\n==AOSIS member states==\nThe member states are:<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.aosis.org/member-states/ |title=Member states |access-date=2019-08-16 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120401053746/http://aosis.info/aomembers/ |archive-date=2012-04-01 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-break}}\nIn the [[Caribbean]]:\n* (16 countries)\n*{{Flag|Antigua and Barbuda}}\n*{{Flag|Bahamas}}\n*{{Flag|Barbados}}\n*{{Flag|Belize}}\n*{{Flag|Cuba}}\n*{{Flag|Dominica}}\n*{{Flag|Dominican Republic}}\n*{{Flag|Grenada}}\n*{{Flag|Guyana}}\n*{{Flag|Haiti}}\n*{{Flag|Jamaica}}\n*{{Flag|Saint Kitts and Nevis}}\n*{{Flag|Saint Lucia}}\n*{{Flag|Saint Vincent and the Grenadines}}\n*{{Flag|Suriname}}\n*{{Flag|Trinidad and Tobago}}\n\n\nIn the [[Atlantic Ocean]], [[Indian Ocean]] and [[South China Sea]]:\n* (8 countries)\n*{{Flag|Cabo Verde}}\n*{{Flag|Comoros}}\n*{{Flag|Guinea-Bissau}}\n*{{Flag|Maldives}}\n*{{Flag|Mauritius}}\n*{{Flag|S\u00e3o Tom\u00e9 and Pr\u00edncipe}}\n*{{Flag|Seychelles}}\n*{{Flag|Singapore}}\n\n{{col-break}}\n\nIn the [[Pacific Ocean]]:\n* (15 countries)\n*{{Flag|Cook Islands}}\n*{{Flag|Fiji}}\n*{{Flag|Kiribati}}\n*{{Flag|Marshall Islands}}\n*{{Flag|Federated States of Micronesia}}\n*{{Flag|Nauru}}\n*{{Flag|Niue}}\n*{{Flag|Palau}}\n*{{Flag|Papua New Guinea}}\n*{{Flag|Samoa}}\n*{{Flag|Solomon Islands}}\n*{{Flag|Timor-Leste}}\n*{{Flag|Tonga}}\n*{{Flag|Tuvalu}}\n*{{Flag|Vanuatu}}\n\n{{col-break}}\n[[Image:AOSIS members.png|thumb|380px|right|AOSIS members in dark green; observers in light green (as of March 2008).]]\n\n{{col-end}}\n\nAOSIS also has five observers: [[American Samoa]], [[Guam]], [[Netherlands Antilles]], [[Puerto Rico]], and the [[United States Virgin Islands]].\n\n==Chairmanship==\n*[[Robert Van Lierop]] (Vanuatu) 1991-1994\n*Annette des Iles (Trinidad and Tobago) 1994-1997\n*[[Tuiloma Neroni Slade]] (Samoa) 1997-2002\n*[[Jagdish Koonjul]] (Mauritius) 2002-2005\n*[[Enele Sopoaga]] (acting) (Tuvalu) 2005-2006\n*[[Julian R. Hunte]] (Saint Lucia) 2006\n*Angus Friday (Grenada) 2006-2009\n*[[Dessima Williams]] (Grenada) 2009-2011\n*[[Marlene Moses]] (Nauru) 2012\u20132014\n*[[Ahmed Sareer]] (Maldives) 2015\u20132017\n*[[Ali Naseer Mohamed]] (Maldives) 2017\u20132018\n*[[Lois Michele Young]] (Belize) 2019\u2013present<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aosis.org/about|title=About AOSIS|publisher=AOSIS - Alliance of Small Island States}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[ACP countries|Africa, the Caribbean and the Pacific]] (ACP)\n*[[Barbados Programme of Action]] (BPOA)\n*[[Climate change mitigation]]\n*[[Islands First]]\n*[[Least Developed Countries]] (LDC)\n*[[World Ocean Conference]]\n*[[Politics of global warming]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://aosis.org Official website]\n\n[[Category:Intergovernmental environmental organizations]]\n[[Category:Climate change organizations]]\n[[Category:Small Island Developing States]]\n[[Category:1990 establishments]]\n[[Category:Organizations based in New York City]]\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=January 2013}}\n\n'''Alliance of Small Island States''' ('''AOSIS''') is an [[intergovernmental organization]] of [[wikt:low lying|low-lying]] [[coast]]al and small [[island country|island countries]]. Established in 1990, the main purpose of the alliance is to consolidate the voices of [[Small Island Developing States]] (SIDS) to address [[global warming]]. AOSIS has been very active from its inception, putting forward the first draft text in the [[Kyoto Protocol]] negotiations as early as 1994. At the [[2013 United Nations Climate Change Conference|2013 Warsaw climate change conference]], AOSIS also pushed for the establishment of an international mechanism on loss and damages stressed by the wreckage of [[Supertyphoon Haiyan]].<ref>{{cite web|title=For Immediate Release: Small Islands Call For Urgency in Warsaw in Wake of Deadly Typhoon|date=11 November 2013|website=AOSIS|url=http://aosis.org/for-immediate-release-small-islands-call-for-urgency-in-warsaw-in-wake-of-deadly-typhoon/|access-date=12 December 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141026120745/http://aosis.org/for-immediate-release-small-islands-call-for-urgency-in-warsaw-in-wake-of-deadly-typhoon/|archive-date=26 October 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> As the existence of many AOSIS states are put at risk by climate change AOSIS has threatened lawsuits. The results of a recent review of the literature <ref>{{cite journal | author = Heidari Negin, Pearce Joshua M | year = 2016 | title = A Review of Greenhouse Gas Emission Liabilities as the Value of Renewable Energy for Mitigating Lawsuits for Climate Change Related Damages | url = https://www.academia.edu/19418589/A_Review_of_Greenhouse_Gas_Emission_Liabilities_as_the_Value_of_Renewable_Energy_for_Mitigating_Lawsuits_for_Climate_Change_Related_Damages |journal=[[Renewable and Sustainable Energy Reviews]] |volume = 55 | issue = | pages = 899\u2013908 | doi = 10.1016/j.rser.2015.11.025 }}</ref> show that potential liability for [[climate change]]-related losses for the Alliance of Small Island States is over $570 trillion.\n\nMany of the member states were present at the December [[2009 United Nations Climate Change Conference]] ([[COP15]]). [[Democracy Now!]] reported that members from the [[island state]] of [[Tuvalu]] interrupted a session of the [[2009 United Nations Climate Change Conference]] on 10 December 2009 to demand that global temperature rise be limited to 1.5 [[\u00b0C]] instead of the proposed 2&nbsp;\u00b0C.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.democracynow.org/2009/12/10/citing_its_survival_pacific_island_of|title=Citing Its Survival, Pacific Island of Tuvalu Interrupts Copenhagen Summit to Call for Binding Climate Commitments|website=Democracy Now!}}</ref><ref>\n{{Cite journal\n | year=2011\n | author=[[United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change]] (UNFCCC)\n | title=Conference of the Parties&nbsp;\u2013 Sixteenth Session: Decision 1/CP.16: The Cancun Agreements: Outcome of the work of the Ad Hoc Working Group on Long-term Cooperative Action under the Convention (English): Paragraph 4\n | publisher=UNFCCC\n | location=UNFCCC Secretariat: [[Bonn]], Germany\n | page=3\n | url=http://unfccc.int/resource/docs/2010/cop16/eng/07a01.pdf#page=2\n | format=PDF\n | ref=harv\n\n}} \"(...) deep cuts in global greenhouse gas emissions are required according to science, and as documented in the Fourth Assessment Report of the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change, with a view to reducing global greenhouse gas emissions so as to hold the increase in global average temperature below {{val|2|u=\u00b0C}} above preindustrial levels\"</ref>\n\nAOSIS has a membership of 44 states, of which 39 are members of the [[United Nations]] and five are [[Observer status|observers]] from all around the world. The alliance represents 28% of the [[developing countries]], and 20% of the [[Member states of the United Nations|UN's total membership]].\n\n==AOSIS member states==\nThe member states are:<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.aosis.org/member-states/ |title=Member states |access-date=2019-08-16 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120401053746/http://aosis.info/aomembers/ |archive-date=2012-04-01 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-break}}\nIn the [[Caribbean]]:\n* (16 countries)\n*{{Flag|Antigua and Barbuda}}\n*{{Flag|Bahamas}}\n*{{Flag|Barbados}}\n*{{Flag|Belize}}\n*{{Flag|Cuba}}\n*{{Flag|Dominica}}\n*{{Flag|Dominican Republic}}\n*{{Flag|Grenada}}\n*{{Flag|Guyana}}\n*{{Flag|Haiti}}\n*{{Flag|Jamaica}}\n*{{Flag|Saint Kitts and Nevis}}\n*{{Flag|Saint Lucia}}\n*{{Flag|Saint Vincent and the Grenadines}}\n*{{Flag|Suriname}}\n*{{Flag|Trinidad and Tobago}}\n\n\nIn the [[Atlantic Ocean]], [[Indian Ocean]] and [[South China Sea]]:\n* (8 countries)\n*{{Flag|Cabo Verde}}\n*{{Flag|Comoros}}\n*{{Flag|Guinea-Bissau}}\n*{{Flag|Maldives}}\n*{{Flag|Mauritius}}\n*{{Fla